<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">Anchor question</div>
  How do you decide who's right when everyone has a legitimate claim?
</div>

<div class="prose">
  <p>Unit 5 names a skill the year has been building toward: <strong>perspective-taking</strong>. In <a href="/units/unit-2/">Unit 2</a> you wrote to one audience (Greater Chennai Corporation planners). In <a href="/units/unit-4/">Unit 4</a> you defended recommendations to that same audience. In Unit 5 you do something harder — you argue from a perspective that may not be your own, in a room with peers arguing from competing perspectives, where all positions have legitimate claims and no one position will fully win.</p>
  <p>The summative — the <a href="/units/unit-5/assessment-water-stakeholders/">Water Stakeholders Map + Position Paper</a> — is the fourth major deliverable of the year. The Stakeholder Roundtable in Block 9 is the fourth defense in the year-long arc and the first one with a multi-stakeholder negotiation format (not Q&amp;A). You'll predict 3+ competing positions, prepare 4+ challenge responses, and propose at least one compromise move in real time.</p>
  <p><strong>U5 is taught in three sections this year using slightly different scaffolds.</strong> Section A builds custom AI partners on BoodleBox (the Boodle Build Assignment — students <em>build</em> their own Stakeholder Voice bot for their chosen stakeholder). Section B uses pre-built Flint guided tutors. Section C uses paper-based Stakeholder Profile Packs (no AI). Each scaffold is designed to teach the same perspective-taking skill — they're pedagogically distinct, not quality-ranked. We're measuring which approach produces what outcomes. Your section's specific tools will be introduced on Day 1.</p>
  <p><strong>The Cauvery dispute is local and politically charged.</strong> Students with inherited views from Tamil Nadu or Karnataka families may find it hard to take an opposite-perspective stakeholder role — that's understood. The 8-case roster is designed for distance: if Cauvery is too close, Colorado / Nile / Aral / Mekong / Indus let you build the same perspective-taking skill in a context that isn't your family's dinner conversation. Stretch (a non-default perspective) is encouraged but not required.</p>
</div>

<section aria-label="Unit 5 blocks" style="margin-top: 24px;">
  <h2 style="font-size: 22px; color: var(--ink); margin-bottom: 12px;">The nine blocks</h2>
  <div class="section-grid">
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-5/block-1/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 1 — Water Cycle + Reservoirs</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Water-cycle diagram with reservoirs, fluxes, and residence times. Names the stakeholders in the Cauvery dispute as the anchor case.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-5/block-2/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 2 — Watersheds + Water Budgets</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Watershed mechanics. Calculate input/storage/output water budgets. Distinguish surface water from groundwater.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-5/block-3/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 3 — Groundwater + Aquifers</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Aquifer recharge + over-pumping + saltwater intrusion. Stakeholder mapping introduced — who is affected, who has voice.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-5/block-4/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 4 — Water Quality + Pollution</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Pollution types + measurement. Reading the 8 water-rights case cards. Each card summarized in one sentence; narrow to 2-3 candidates.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-5/block-5/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 5 — Water Rights + Stakeholders Map Assigned</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Case + stakeholder perspective locked today. Stakeholders Map + Position Paper assigned. The hard pedagogical pick: stretch vs. own-view-default.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-5/block-6/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 6 — Cauvery Deep Dive + Stakeholders Map Started</div>
      <div class="card-desc">First major Position Paper work day. Cauvery case study + Bangalore worked-example Stakeholders Map demo + students start their own 7-field map.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-5/block-7/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 7 — Counter-Argument + Stakeholder Voice AI</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Stakeholder Voice AI introduced. Identify strongest counter to your position; respond without strawmanning.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-5/block-8/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 8 — Drafting + Roundtable Rehearsal</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Final drafting + Roundtable rehearsal. Predict 3+ competing stakeholder positions; prepare 4+ challenge responses.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-5/block-9/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 9 — Stakeholder Roundtable + Unit Close</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Submission + live multi-stakeholder Roundtable. Negotiation format (not Q&A). Unit-close reflection + U6 preview.</div>
    </a>
  </div>
</section>

<section aria-label="Unit 5 assessment" style="margin-top: 32px;">
  <h2 style="font-size: 22px; color: var(--ink); margin-bottom: 12px;">Assessment</h2>
